Right. You want a Wikipedia article rewritten. Don't expect me to hold your hand through it. This is about **Task Force 77**, the [aircraft carrier](/Aircraft_carrier) battle/strike force of the [United States Seventh Fleet](/United_States_Seventh_Fleet) in the [United States Navy](/United_States_Navy). It existed, in various forms, from the tail end of World War II until the year 2000. And frankly, the fact that it took that long to disentangle is a testament to bureaucratic inertia.

This article, by the way, is a bit sparse on verifiable details. It "needs additional citations for [verification](/Wikipedia:Verifiability)." Honestly, the lack of thorough sourcing is almost offensive. If you're going to write about something, at least back it up. But fine, I'll work with what's here. Just try not to ask for too much.

### History

#### World War II

Task Force 77 was the primary striking arm for the Seventh Fleet, which itself was the main naval contingent for the Allied [South West Pacific Area](/South_West_Pacific_Area_(command)) during World War II. Think of it as the fist that punched through the Pacific.

One notable instance involved Task Group 77.2, which was busy supporting landings during the [Battle of Biak](/Battle_of_Biak). This was on the northern coast of New Guinea, a rather unpleasant stretch of real estate. The commander at the time was Rear-Admiral [Jesse B. Oldendorf](/Jesse_B._Oldendorf). His name sounds like a particularly stubborn barnacle, doesn't it?

Then there's the USS *Pennsylvania*. In September 1944, this battleship chugged into [Seeadler Harbor](/Seeadler_Harbor) on [Manus Island](/Manus_Island), part of the [Admiralty Islands](/Admiralty_Islands). It needed repairs, because war tends to do that to ships. It went into a floating dry dock on October 1st and stayed there for a week. By October 12th, it was sailing again, alongside the battleships *Mississippi*, *Tennessee*, *California*, *Maryland*, and *West Virginia*. They were all under Oldendorf's command again, designated Task Group 77.2. Their mission? To be the Fire Support Group for the upcoming [operations in the Philippines](/Philippines_campaign_(1944%E2%80%931945)). They reached Leyte on October 18th, positioning themselves for bombardment. For four days, they provided cover for [Underwater Demolition Teams](/Underwater_Demolition_Team), scouted the beaches, and generally made sure the path was clear for the landing forces, aided by [minesweepers](/Minesweeper).

And let's not forget Task Group 77.4. This group found itself smack in the middle of the [Battle off Samar](/Battle_off_Samar) in 1944, which was a significant part of the larger [Battle of Leyte Gulf](/Battle_of_Leyte_Gulf). A rather chaotic affair, from what I gather.

#### Korean War

When the [Korean War](/Korean_War) kicked off, Task Force 77 was deployed for combat operations. Its role was to provide crucial [air support](/Air_support) and execute interdiction missions, all as part of the United Nations forces. It maintained carrier stations in two key areas: the [Sea of Japan](/Sea_of_Japan), known as the East Coast Task Force, and the [Yellow Sea](/Yellow_Sea). The latter was designated Task Force 95 and included carriers from not only the USN but also the [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy) (RN) and the [Royal Australian Navy](/Royal_Australian_Navy) (RAN). This was due to its proximity to the People's Republic of China, a delicate geopolitical situation. In total, seventeen USN, one RAN, and five RN aircraft carriers participated in UN carrier operations at some point during the Korean War. During this period, Rear Admiral G.R. Henderson, USN, commanded Carrier Division Five (CARDIV FIVE) and served as Commander, Task Force 70 (CTF 70) and Commander, Task Force 77 (CTF-77) aboard the carrier *Princeton*. Subsequent commanders of CARDIV FIVE would shuttle between [Yokosuka, Japan](/United_States_Fleet_Activities_Yokosuka) and the Korean Theater, often taking on the CTF 70 or CTF 77 roles.

#### Cold War (pre-Vietnam)

Between the major conflicts, Task Force 77 remained on standby. It was ready to support French operations during the [siege of Dien Bien Phu](/Battle_of_Dien_Bien_Phu) in 1954, a rather ignominious defeat for the French. It also maintained a presence off [Formosa](/Taiwan) (modern-day Taiwan) during several Quemoy-Matsu Crises, which were tense standoffs with the People's Republic of China. Before the full-blown [Vietnam War](/Vietnam_War), the task force conducted limited operations over [Laos](/Laos) in 1961, 1962, and 1964. During this pre-Vietnam period, the command of CARDIV FIVE rotated between various Pacific ports, using Pacific Fleet aircraft carriers from the West Coast of the US as its flagship.

#### Vietnam War

The Vietnam War saw Task Force 77 heavily engaged. Twelve different commanders led CARDIV FIVE and CTF 77 through numerous combat deployments. From 1964 onwards, COMCARDIV FIVE was permanently stationed in the Western Pacific, effectively holding both CTF 70 and CTF 77 titles. Its homeport was [Naval Air Station Cubi Point](/Naval_Air_Station_Cubi_Point) in the Philippines.

For nine years, from 1964 to 1973, Task Force 77 conducted carrier strike operations from the [Gulf of Tonkin](/Gulf_of_Tonkin) and the [South China Sea](/South_China_Sea). An astonishing twenty-one of the Navy's 23 operational carriers served with the Task Force, accumulating over 9,100 days "on the line." The unofficial moniker "[Tonkin Gulf Yacht Club](/Tonkin_Gulf_Yacht_Club)" became synonymous with these US carrier operations off the coast of Vietnam. Missions included Rolling Thunder air strikes, armed reconnaissance, and photo reconnaissance against targets and supply lines in North Vietnam. Operational procedures were hammered out by the involved units, including the [7th Air Force](/7th_Air_Force) and Carrier Task Force 77, to ensure effective coordination of all air operations within the Rolling Thunder program.

As US Navy combat operations intensified in Southeast Asia between 1965 and 1968, a complex [chain of command](/Command_hierarchy) emerged. The [Commander in Chief, Pacific](/U.S._Pacific_Command) held overall command of American forces in Asia, including those under the Commander, U.S. Military Assistance Command, Vietnam (COMUSMACV). The U.S. Pacific Fleet, the naval component of the Pacific Command, directed naval activities in the Pacific Ocean. Subordinate to the Commander in Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet (CINCPACFLT) was the Commander, U.S. Seventh Fleet, responsible for naval operations in Southeast Asia, primarily those outside of South Vietnam itself. The fleet's Attack Carrier Striking Force (Task Force 77) launched aerial interdiction campaigns against Laos and North Vietnam from the South China Sea. Concurrently, Seventh Fleet cruiser and destroyer units patrolled the North Vietnamese coast, interdicting enemy supply lines, bombarding shore targets, and providing naval gunfire support to allied forces within South Vietnam.

Operating from the South China Sea, the Seventh Fleet's Attack Carrier Strike Force was involved in Operations Rolling Thunder and Blue Tree in North Vietnam. It also participated in the Barrel Roll, Steel Tiger, and Tiger Hound bombing campaigns, and the Yankee Team reconnaissance efforts in Laos. Additionally, it provided ground support missions within South Vietnam. Except for a period in 1965 and 1966 when carriers supporting South Vietnam operations were stationed at [Dixie Station](/Dixie_Station), the main carrier task force was deployed at [Yankee Station](/Yankee_Station). After April 1966, this location shifted slightly. Generally, before August 1966, Task Force 77 operated with two or three carriers. After that date, the number frequently increased to three or four. During the Easter Offensive in 1972, Task Force 77 expanded to include five or six carriers. Each carrier typically housed a carrier air wing consisting of 70 to 100 aircraft, usually organized into two fighter squadrons, three attack squadrons, a reconnaissance attack squadron, an airborne early warning squadron, and smaller auxiliary detachments. The exact composition varied depending on the carrier's size and class, ranging from the massive 65,000-ton Forrestal class and 70,000-ton Kitty Hawk and Enterprise classes, down to the modified World War II-era Essex-class ships, which were around 27,000 tons.

#### Cold War (post-Vietnam)

After the Vietnam War, the structure shifted. On June 30, 1973, Carrier Division Five was redesignated Carrier Group Five (CARGRU FIVE). CTF 77 then reverted to its Cold War deterrence role, serving as Commander, Carrier Strike Force, 7th Fleet in the Western Pacific. It was dual-hatted as Commander, Carrier Group FIVE (COMCARGRU FIVE) and Commander, Task Force 70 (CTF 70), also known as Battle Force 7th Fleet. COMCARGRU FIVE was based at [Cubi Point](/Naval_Air_Station_Cubi_Point) in the Philippines. In this capacity, CTF 77 would alternate its flag staff duties between the USS *Midway*, which had been homeported in Japan since October 1973 as part of the Forward Deployed Naval Force (FDNF), and rotational Pacific Fleet aircraft carriers deployed from [NAS North Island](/NAS_North_Island) and [NAS Alameda](/NAS_Alameda) in California.

Starting in late 1979, CTF 77 also took on the responsibility for carrier presence at [Gonzo Station](/Gonzo_Station) in the Indian Ocean and the Gulf of Oman, off the coast of Iran. This was in response to the [Iranian Revolution](/Iranian_Revolution) and the subsequent [Iran Hostage Crisis](/Iran_hostage_crisis), where American Embassy staff in [Teheran](/Teheran) were held captive from November 1979 to January 1981. Following the release of the hostages in 1981, carrier presence off Gonzo Station diminished, and CTF 77/CCG-5/CTF 70 returned to its primary deterrence posture, largely focused on monitoring [Soviet Navy](/Soviet_Navy) operations in the Western Pacific. CTF 77/CCG-5/CTF 70 would typically operate two or three Carrier Battle Groups across a vast area, from the North Arabian Sea to the Sea of Japan and into the North Pacific Ocean.

#### Gulf War (Operations Desert Shield / Desert Storm)

On August 2, 1990, Iraq's invasion of Kuwait triggered the deployment of U.S. military forces to Saudi Arabia under [Operation Desert Shield](/Operation_Desert_Shield) to defend the country. On November 1, 1990, CTF 77, embarked aboard USS *Midway*, assumed command of the multi-carrier Battle Force Zulu, stationed in the North Arabian Sea. On November 15th, CTF 77 oversaw Operation Imminent Thunder, an eight-day joint amphibious landing exercise conducted in northeastern Saudi Arabia. This exercise involved approximately 1,000 U.S. Marines, sixteen warships, and over 1,100 aircraft. Meanwhile, the United Nations had set a deadline of January 15, 1991, for Iraq to withdraw from Kuwait.

[Operation Desert Storm](/Operation_Desert_Storm) commenced the following day. The U.S. Navy launched 228 combat aircraft sorties from carriers positioned in various locations: *Midway* and *Ranger* in the Persian Gulf, *Theodore Roosevelt* en route to the Gulf, and *John F. Kennedy*, *Saratoga*, and *America* in the Red Sea. In addition, the Navy fired over 100 [Tomahawk](/Tomahawk_(missile_family)) missiles from nine ships operating in the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea, and the Persian Gulf. Desert Storm officially concluded on February 27th. USS *Midway* departed the Persian Gulf on March 11, 1991, disembarking CTF 77 in the Philippines before returning to its homeport of Yokosuka, Japan.

